reviewText: I'm not sure what the other reviewer is talking about regarding video quality.  This title *IS* Anamorphic, which means more video information is contained than non-anamorphic, so when the title is stretched back out to 16:9, you don't lose anything.  IOW, there's no reason he should need to use the "zoom" feature on his set.I own 4 or 5 of the MIHP series, and the quality of this one IS the best.  There are a few older titles that aren't anamorphic.Love the "Play just the music" feature too.  I was never a huge goo-goo dolls fan until I saw this.  I like their acoustic tunes better than full band rock and roll.

reviewText: Any fan (casual or die hard) will enjoy this collection of great songs coupled with amazing shots of Alaska. The Dolls seem to really be enjoying themselves, especially Robbie, and you can tell how well it translates into the music. My faves include: the iceberg, the high jump with the locals and Johnny jokingly complaining about the non-smoking bars. I also have the Alanis in the Navajo disc, but this is visually more exciting.

reviewText: Not a bad video. The music was pretty good, Goo Goo Dolls sound pretty much the same "live" as they do on their albums...except John R. is a bit flat at certion places. Be sure to watch the "Just Music" portion, the scenery is some of the more awe inspiring for the whole show.I enjoyed the views of Alaska, and the moutains from the train bit, were beautiful! The "interviews" with the guys were lacking something, John R. is not exactly articulate. But wait till the end, when the "behind the scenes" crew video is shown. That is funny!And one last note; It was nice how the guys were playing with the local kids. They go "mud sliding", and then interview some of the kids. And it is too cute how the little kids are glowing about; "...I can't believe I went mud sliding with the Goo Goo Dolls!!!!!!!!!" -Mud sliding for those of you out there who haven't seen the video, is exactly what it sounds like.Anyway, an all around fun watch. If you like "Music in High Places" this would be one to add to the collection!

reviewText: I first listened to Goo Goo Dolls when watching "City of Angels" with my ex, I gotta thank her for that...It made possible getting deep into one of the bands I most respect for the simple, eager and talented music I've got the pleasure to listen to. I knew these guys for the Billboard Blockbuster songs "Iris", "Slide",etc but knew that I was scoring big purchasing this DVD for these guys can seriously play and yet seriously-and ironically- be a bunch of funny regular guys who mud slide with the local boys and play "here is gone" on a train (darn i couldn't get a couple of tickets for that one!!!). I can't get enough of Alaska and the Goos playing: imagine Acoustic  #3  played in the middle of the bluest stream ever over a pile of ice with a never ending blue sky above...can't right? well it happens here! Playing in bars where u can't smoke yet a musician playing the harmonica is going to die coughing at the end of the song...lol. The local radio stud who weighs at least 350 pounds. Everything, everything is for discovering more about the Goos insights while listening to their heart touching music. Grab it folks while you can. Peace

reviewText: Unlike most live CD's/DVD's this one is very different. The reviews from other readers were very helpful: I have a large screen and surround and the review was dead on - the scenes of Alaska are awesome and the Johnny Reznik is talented enough to pull off their best tunes from their latest project acoustically. Don't expect a typical concert - basically the Goo's and a guitar... much time is spent showing them touring Alaska - but if you are a fan it makes you feel like your hanging out with the boys. Only reason it didn't get 5 stars? Surprisingly, they don't perform "Iris" or "Name" - songs which would seem to be easier to pull off acoustically and are their best sellers. If you are a fan, enjoy cool scenery, and can live with only 7 songs (mostly from "Gutter Flower"), it's worth having in the collection.
summary: Great scenery, solid acoustic performances make this work

reviewText: Been a fan of Goo Goo dolls for awhile and considered them to be at times on the cutting edge with songs like "slide" "broadway" "black baloon" and "Acoustic 3 " all of which are on here in a acoustic way. John Rzeznik does most of the commentary and its set in alaska which provides some unbelievable scenery. This is not your bang them up GGD but  reflective pieces especially with John on appreciation of where they have come from. Its a good dvd for sitting with your significant other to enjoy a short version of 40 minutes of 7 songs, but was looking for alittle more... Not disapointed to have it
